wh-qu1: There are no WH-interrogatives with missing copula/DO (no questions like 'Where she at?' or 'What you want?').
wh-qu2: No WH-questions or embedded WH-clauses with non-SAE inversion patterns occur.
existential-it: There is no existential 'it' construction; no clause uses 'it' where SAE would use 'there' to introduce existence.
demonstrative-them: 'thems' appears as an object pronoun ('wave thems down'), not as a determiner before a noun meaning 'those'.
appositive-pleonastic-pronoun: No NP is followed by a co-referential pronoun in the same grammatical role within the same clause.
bin: No 'BIN/been' appears without 'have' as an aspectual marker.
verb-stem: No bare verb clearly functions as a finite past-tense form with explicit past cues; 'seem like…' is ambiguous and not clearly past-marked.
past-tense-swap: 'did saw' is nonstandard but not a participle/past-form swap as defined; no cases like 'seen' for simple past or 'had bit' for participle are present.
zero-rel-pronoun: No subject relative clause lacks an overt relative pronoun modifying a noun.
preterite-had: No 'had' + verb is used to express simple past (no forms like 'had went/ran' with simple-past meaning).
bare-got: No present-possessive 'got' without 'have' is used.

sentence: And uh, I did saw someone climbing up    uh, uh I guess it was a sheet, to try to get off of  something, trying to get  uh, uh, up on the roof.
zero-poss: No noun–noun possessive or nonstandard possessive pronoun; no possessive relation is expressed without SAE marking.
zero-copula: The clause has overt BE: “I guess it was a sheet,” so no BE deletion occurs.
double-tense: Although “did saw” shows past on auxiliary and verb, the rule targets duplicated past morphology within a single word, which is not present.
be-construction: No uninflected 'be' with habitual meaning appears; only “was” occurs.
resultant-done: No preverbal 'done' marking completive aspect appears.
finna: No form of finna/finta/fitna is present.
come: No stance/evaluative 'come' before a VP; 'come' does not occur.
double-modal: No sequence of two modals (e.g., might could) occurs.
multiple-neg: There are no negative elements in the clause.
neg-inversion: No clause-initial negative auxiliary precedes the subject.
n-inv-neg-concord: No clause shows both subject and verb with overt negative marking.
zero-3sg-pres-s: No 3sg present-tense verb lacks -s; the finite 3sg clause is past (“it was”).
is-was-gen: “Was” agrees with 3sg subject 'it'; no generalized is/was with nonstandard agreement.
zero-pl-s: No clearly plural noun appears without plural -s.
double-object: No personal dative pattern like “I got me NP”; no coreferential subject + object pronoun + NP sequence.
wh-qu1: There is no WH-question in the utterance.
wh-qu2: There is no WH-question or embedded WH-clause with non-SAE inversion.
existential-it: “It” in “I guess it was a sheet” is referential, not existential.
demonstrative-them: No use of 'them' as a demonstrative determiner before a noun.
appositive-pleonastic-pronoun: No NP followed by a redundant co-referential pronoun in the same grammatical role.
verb-stem: No bare verb with clear past reference; the past is marked as “did saw”/“was,” not a stem used for past.
past-tense-swap: “Did saw” is not a participle/past swap; the rule targets forms like 'seen' as preterite or 'had bit,' which are absent.
zero-rel-pronoun: No finite subject relative clause modifying a noun without an overt relative pronoun is present.
preterite-had: No 'had' + verb used to express simple past occurs.
bare-got: No use of 'got' as a present possessive verb ('have') appears.
